Nutrition of children suffering from obesity: No breakfast or sausage for dinner
More than one third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 were overweight; while 9 per cent of pupils were overweight, 5 per cent were obese.
According to a recent study, children suffering from obesity usually come from unhealthy families.
Once again, we see the importance of the environment and the behaviours accompanying the human being for his or her healthy development.
For example, sausage appears on tables of children suffering from obesity almost twice as often as in families with children with normal weight.
More than 19 per cent of children suffering from obesity ate fries for dinner on the eve of an educational event called Obesity is not an accident.
Moreover, the families of children suffering from obesity do not engage in sports; however, this is true of the majority of families of modern school children - only 15 per cent of the children said that their parents took time to engage in sports at least once a week.
The study was carried out among 900 children.
The study was carried out at the end of the last school year; nearly 900 primary students throughout Bohemia participated in it.
Obesity was not an accident for the second consecutive year, with the support of the insurance company Všeobecná zdravotní pojišovna and Unilever.
To date, more than 12,000 students in grades 4 to 8 have joined the project.
Good nutrition and sufficient sporting burden are the main determinants of the rapidly growing number of children who suffer from either overweight or obesity.
"For example, only half of the respondents said that they eat five meals a day, a lunch lunch lunch luncheon, and that's one of the essential conditions for proper diet," says one of the findings of the study.
No lunch and no sausage at night.
Experts warn that even relative details, such as permanent family breakfast, are important for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of school families eat breakfast together.
Most families have separate breakfasts.
The worst discovery is that in every tenth family, people don't eat breakfast at all.
And yet breakfast is the basis of the right day's diet.
The study found that fried food is more commonly used in families with children suffering from obesity.
Almost everyone, regardless of weight, drinks sweet, cool drinks every day (70%).
Although more than 40 per cent of children regularly engage in sports, this figure is reduced by more than half, to 15 per cent, when it comes to their parents.
Make your own menu.
In another part of the study, selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) were asked to draw up their own menus based on the products offered and based on their tastes and preferences.
"The preference for food for Czech children aged 12-15 is far from the ideal of healthy nutrition."
Their favorite food includes a large number of flour, meat, and sweet dishes.
“A particular concern is the popularity of sweet, cool drinks”, says the final part of the study.
As the main meal, the pasta defeated the bird with a small margin.
However, children showed little interest in beans, fish, and vegetables.
Seeking a Healthy Lifestyle
The study also showed that children are prepared to change their eating habits provided that they are provided with relevant information.
“Many members of the monitoring group showed a significant shift in preferences towards healthy food when they completed the study on Obesity - it's not an accident”, says the project's outcome.
This was particularly noticeable, for example, in the case of sweet, cool drinks - more children began to prefer them to just water.
In addition, children were more likely to observe birds and fish as the main dish, limiting the number of sweet dishes and baking.
