V Need for Speed: The run takes place in America.
Overview
What was supposed to be a careless walk turned into a routine morning trip to work because of a series of totally inappropriate and careless mistakes.
Ambiences had been met to a certain extent, but that was not important, since no one clearly wanted to do any extra work.
Before the release with the new version with the subtitle "Run," there was a lot of hope.
It was expected to move the previous series of "Ned For Speed" into a new direction; demonstration versions showed that the game would take a decent place in the genre of the race games.
We were curious to see the parts of the game where the main character got out of the car and ran.
As is often the case with NFS, in the end, much is different from what we expected.
The game is a pretty good arcade race, but the general impression is eroded by some unnecessary errors that have been present in this series of games for several years.
Which means it's not really a mistake, it's a demonstration of the inexplicable laziness of the developers.
The adventure starts very well.
You're becoming part of a story whose main hero, Jack, solves some personal problems by taking part in an illegal race through America.
You get in a car on the west coast in San Francisco, and it's your job to get to New York first.
This idea has some interesting features.
The route consists of 10 stages divided into more than 50 races.
This means that each race takes its own route, and the individual stages take place in a diverse and interesting environment.
So it doesn't feel like the game is the same all the time.
Although the charts are at the same level as in the previous parts of the series, it is a pleasure to look at some of the tracks.
Still, the game does not give rise to strong emotions.
Although driving through the desert, the autumn suburbs, or high in the snowy mountains is a pleasure.
Besides, the race occasionally revives an unusual detail.
In the desert, for example, you find yourself in a sandstorm that significantly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you have to be careful not to get caught in a hole.
Individual races are fairly well organized.
There are only a few varieties, but that's enough.
For a while, you're trying to outrun a few rivals (in fact, a normal race); then you're trying to improve time (a standard race with a second meter); or you're competing with one adversary.
Among other things, from time to time, you run into a police force that makes your task even more difficult.
The components outside the car are new.
It's just an interactive animation where most of the time Jack runs away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right time.
It's not complicated.
Although it is surprising that these fragments are much smaller than you would expect (three to be accurate).
In fact, it turns out that it's good for a game because it's not boring; given all the above, it's one of the things that makes the game more fun.
The race model follows the tracks of the previous models.
This means that it is no longer something special, but it cannot be considered a disadvantage.
If you're looking for a real life simulation, you're going to have to look elsewhere.
Still, this driving model is very good for dynamic racing, although better options can be found in the marketplace.
So far, so good.
However, after a while, problems begin.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not that good.
You don't expect such a game to be a complex transformation and collision, but if you don't have any idea how your machine will behave, something's wrong.
Normally, bypassing or passing cars in a dense flow, you sometimes touch another car slightly, but sometimes, in a virtually similar situation, your car becomes rabidly twisted.
Or she's broken.
It's not that important because of the restart system, but it's enough to ruin the fun.
Restarts are designed so that if you break down or go far off the track, the game returns you to the point where it stopped.
However, only five relaunchs are available for each race.
If you use them all, you'll have to start the race from the beginning.
It's useful if something doesn't work out, but you can't rely on it completely.
Sometimes restarting is not enough, and you have to memorize a separate section of the race.
An important disadvantage of play is the fact that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some corners have to go in a certain way, otherwise you just don't fit in.
In other cases, you meet civilian cars in a certain location in the same configuration, regardless of whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds sooner or a minute later.
This is particularly frustrating in situations where you see your opponent passing easily between two cars moving in the opposite direction, whereas when you are there, the machines are already positioned in such a way that you need to either travel around them or slow down.
It doesn't matter when you're around them; it's always the way things happen in front of you.
The opponents have other advantages.
During the game, you find several places where, regardless of time, the same rival overtakes you in the same place.
It's especially obvious at the end of the game, on a long bridge where you're driving in the opposite direction.
Obviously, your opponent must stand before you no matter what.
The thing is, when he's driving in front of you, he's making your view worse, resulting in one or more accidents in this area.
You can understand an attempt to make the game more interesting and filled with adrenaline, but it's so obvious that it's starting to get annoying fast.
It's a shame, because despite the simple model of driving, the game is interesting and sometimes so full of events that you don't have time to pay attention to what's going on around you.
It doesn't matter what makes you bored -- a concept with fifty unique tracks, a race sequence or something.
The idea of changing cars during the race is unusual.
You need to track the gas stations along the way, because that's where your car can switch, despite the fact that in most cases the one you already have is quite enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
Sports machines are suitable for cities; powerful American cars for direct highway sections; and exotic super-sport vehicles for technical driving, for example, on curved mountain tracks.
The main mode is closely linked to the challenge mode; it is a race on individual plots that you will learn during the game.
Here you win for your personal business, both medals and glasses common to challenges and story regimes.
Many possibilities are available for higher driving levels, ranging from cars to profile data.
In addition, the profile is related to the online function Autolog, which, among other things, compares the results you have achieved with those of other players, and provides communication to the public.
Here's another weakness that's hard to understand; it's an example from the last race in sequence.
You and your car get into the subway tunnel (let's think so) where you run down the rails in the dark (let's think so).
Your speedometer shows the numbers from 150 to 200 km/h (let's say so) when a subway train suddenly hits you from behind, turning your car into a pile of scrap metal.
For a few days, our editorial debated whether at the time of the game's creation, no one really thought for a second, or whether its creators really think we're such idiots.
The technical element of the game is not very special; but the overall impression from the video series is mostly pleasant, sometimes even amazing.
Although it is unfortunate that in some critical moments, the quality of recording is sometimes reduced quite strongly.
This is especially true of a large number of participants, where good recordings would not be very helpful to you, too.
Sound's fine; soundtrack's on the amateur.
In order to please as wide a youth audience as possible, the soundtrack's "compositions from different styles"; but it's unlikely that a lot of people will buy a game because of its music.
The general impression of Need for Speed is that the escape is rather messy.
If the game were to avoid obviously unnecessary mistakes, we could honestly say that Run is the best part of the NFS in the last few years.
In any case, the game leaves a feeling of incompleteness.
Of course, it's a good fun, but prepare yourself to be blinded as a spotlight at the airport.
