Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five government tourism agencies could work in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Because travel to the West was severely restricted, tourist agencies of that time were mostly selling tours to socialist bloc countries.
Thus, during the holidays Czech tourists travelled to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was from 1962 to 1972, when we were able to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, which led to considerable restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
A great paradox of the socialist period was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed to travel individually to socialist countries.
If a Czechoslovakia citizen wanted to go on his own, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter of invitation was needed from that country; otherwise, an individual journey was impossible.
At the time, travel agencies offered to travel to the West, but either they had to wait in line all night, with a sleeping bag, or they had "good friends" in the agency.
And that wasn't all.
Currency permits were necessary for travel to the West, not given to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; without currency permission, it was impossible to obtain money (Western currency) for travel to the West.
Most of the time the Czechs spent their vacations at home, resulting in large numbers of cottages and summer homes, a habit that continues to exist today.
After 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic thus experienced a real revolution.
While until 1989 leave to the GDR or Bulgaria was the culmination of our journeys, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations in countries around the world.
The great paradox, which we no longer understand, is that before 1989 we were unable freely to visit Croatia, which is now the most popular, as it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the very beginning of 1990, the need to obtain a visa to neighbouring countries in Western Europe was lifted, resulting in a huge wave of short trips, mostly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovakia couldn't be satisfied with their travels to the West, and everyone wanted to go there for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents because their income at the time was insufficient for a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism at that time was the desire to bring its own food (conserves, salami, etc.) in order to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a freely convertible Czech crown, and after decades, our tourists are finally free to buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and average income have increased, leading to another important circumstance around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has enabled travel agencies to prepare regular flights by charter airlines, and in comparison with the past, air travel has become incredibly cheap because of the ability to order wholesale discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs did not need a visa to visit virtually all the developed worlds except the US, which made our travels even easier.
The next major event in the history of post-revolution travels occurred in 2000, and a large demand has historically led to the first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have transported Czech tourists to warm exotic countries, and this winter flight from the Czech Republic will take 12 exotic directions.
At present, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
And another important event of this period, symbolizing our post-revolution development, took place in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US cancelled the need for a visa for Czech tourists, and our country has thus permanently joined the world's most developed countries.
For the first time in history in 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their vacations abroad (50.3 per cent); and for the first time in history, they spent more than 15,000 kroner per person during their leave abroad, including their spending at their destination.
