Peter Englund's intense and very kind new book "The Beauty and Pilgrimage: The Personal History of the First World War" begins with a long list of actors that kills the heart.
Here's how to read the following: Cut this page carefully and use it as a bookmark.
You'll get to know these people very closely as Mr. Englund speaks, and this list of actors will be your GPS, your beacon at those moments when, like one of these men and women, you get off the road and get lost in the fog of war.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book he wrote now is unusual, he describes it, quite precisely, as "work on antihistory."
There are few known names, important treaties, or famous battles; there are few ambassadors, clever journalists, or discussions about tactics and military equipment.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, it's a book about what it was like, it's about feelings, experiences, feelings, and a state of spirit.
The book "Beauty and Pilgrimage" combined the experience of 20 more or less unfamiliar men and women, on both sides of the front line, from schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and employees.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Someone gets captured, loses his arm or his leg, goes crazy or dies.
Their lives are flashing here like church candles: new ones are added to many others, and some are extinguished at this time.
Mr. Englund's book is a departure from the standard of historical books.
It's also an amendment to the idea that the First World War was only a gravel war on the West Front.
The Beauty and Pilgrimage provides the panoramas of other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, and East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are hit by bee hives; one of them meets Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; the unsolved problem is the tsetse flies.
It's an exciting book, almost from the beginning.
War covers the lives of these people as a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina, smelling of smokeless powder.
When you're not far from hearing the canon, and you're a woman at home with the kids, will you stay here or run away?
Anyway, who's coming?
Almost no one understands what's going on or why we have to fight this war.
"The lack of facts," observes Mr. Englund, "is filled with speculation, speculation, hopes, fears, obsessions, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumours."
Beauty and Pilgrimage traces the fate of people like Florence Pharmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor of the German High Seas Navy.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other material already published.
Their stories may be scary or exciting, but they are highly alive thanks to Mr. Englund's small moments and fragmentary details.
Many of them are about deprivation and how to deal with it.
When he tells the story of a German schoolgirl, he says, "Erzaz, there's an erzac everywhere."
"Coffee replacement, forged aluminium, fake rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He keeps talking about the eszac food in Germany.
He describes “poultry rice boiled in ovine fat (and decorated with a fake bone made of wood); tobacco made of dried roots and dried potato skin; footwear covered by a tree”.
He notes that there were “837 registered meat substitutes allowed in the production of sausage, 511 registered coffee substitutes”.
Some stories speak of honour and courage.
One American sees himself as the most violent, and says about war, "You feel that at the end of the day, this is what men were made for, not to sit in comfortable chairs with cigarettes and whiskey, an evening paper or a bestseller, and to say that this show is a civilization and that under your shiny shirt there is no barbarian."
On the contrary, a British soldier notices that he is likely to die and that no one will notice or grieve.
"When a person accepts the idea of self-sacrifice, he would like to think it would happen in front of the public," he writes.
But it's the other way around, it's like a "convicted man who's been hanged in secret."
Other comments concern old Europe, which is falling apart, and new types of fear.
"The conflict was increasingly becoming an economic competition," writes Mr. Englund, "a war factory."
He marks the arrival of someone who is called "a new species of the bestiary of the beginning of the century: a beautifully expressed and ideologically convinced mass murderer in a well-mixed suit that organizes a massacre sitting behind a writing table."
People are acting in an unexpected way: the low-level actions are as much heroism.
Mr. Englund spoke about soldiers who tried to get sexually transmitted diseases from prostitutes in order to avoid serving on the front.
"The greatest expression of this can be seen in the trade of gonorrhoeal gnomes that soldiers bought and smeared in their genitals in the hope of reaching the hospital," he writes.
"Every desperate person was wiping it in the eye, which often led to life's blindness."
Translated with the Swedish Peter Graves Proza by Mr. Englund, a flexible but non-brostic, perfectly suited to his humanistic task.
In dozens of small scenes, it shows how the war “released completely uncontrollable forces: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred”.
People are starting to ask why their leaders force them to fight.
The best books about World War I were often indirect, such as "The Great War and Modern Memory" by Paul Fassel or novels such as "On the West Front Without Change" by Erich-Marie Remark, rather than exhaustive historical writings.
