Mission over, Congress is ready for an agreement on Libya.
It seems that the Republicans and Democrats on Capitol Hill are finally ready to agree on something relevant to the insurrection in Libya.
All it took was for the rebellion to succeed, the long-standing dictator Muammar Qaddafi was captured and killed, and the American intervention ended.
On Tuesday, the Senate Foreign Affairs Committee is to consider a resolution put forward by President John Kerry (democracy, Massachusetts) together with Senators John McCain (Republican, Arizona) and Joseph I. Liberman (independent, Connecticut), who praises the Libyans for their successful rebellion and American troops for their “dust”.
“The purpose of this resolution is to pay tribute to the brave people of Libya when they begin to rebuild their country”, said Kerry.
"It is confirmation of the support of both parties for their democratic aspirations."
Language may seem harmless, but no discussion on Libya has yet taken place easily.
This summer, legislators from both parties argued with each other and the White House about the wording of a series of resolutions endorsing or condemning the role of the American army in the NATO mission in Libya.
In June, Kerry and McCain submitted a resolution allowing for the limited use of the United States armed forces in Libya.
The bill was rejected by the House of Representatives by a large majority vote of both parties and was never put to the Senate.
But on the same day that the bill failed in the House of Representatives, the House also did not support a proposal that would reduce the financing of the United States operation in Libya.
This left the American mission in some sort of legislative purgatory – when Congress is annoyed enough to criticize Obama’s approach to the mission, but not angry enough to actually get the ground out of her feet.
Then events overcame Congress's indecision.
In August, Tripoli surrendered to the Libyan rebels and, on 20 October, Gaddafi was killed.
The NATO mission formally ended on 31 October.
Now the Senate can be ready for action.
The resolution of the Foreign Affairs Committee “reveals the Libyan people for their extraordinary courage and endurance in their quest for freedom” and thanks the men and women of the United States Armed Forces and their coalition partners who participated in the military operation to protect the Libyan people for their extraordinary courage and professionalism.”
The resolution also “confirms the national interest of the United States in a successful and irreversible transition to democracy in Libya”.
Will the new measures receive full support from the Foreign Affairs Council or divide legislators like the June Bill?
Senator Richard G. Luger, the leader of the Republicans on the Committee, opposed the latter.
Luger's representative said on Monday that he had not yet seen the last version of the bill.
On the other side of the Capitol, the House of Representatives should vote this week for a constitutional amendment that requires a balanced budget, a primary legislative priority for almost every republican and some Democrats in Congress.
