Other legislators have not yet been able to bring their amendments to the plenary, but not because they have not tried.
The Gudlat amendment is only one of the 68 constitutional amendments affecting a wide range of issues that have been introduced in this meeting.
Some were duplicated - the same bill was introduced in the House of Representatives and in the Senate - others were minor variations.
There are at least 15 revisions to the balanced budget only in the House of Representatives and more to “control of federal expenditures”.
Some of them are also identical, but give their authors, mostly newly elected Republicans who wish to decorate their resumes, the opportunity to boast that they have “promoted” such a proposal.
The Budget Control Act, which passed in August, required both the House of Representatives and the Senate to vote in favour of the balanced budget amendment.
In March, 58 senators voted in favour of a non-binding resolution supporting the idea of such an amendment.
In addition to the budget, some congressmen wish to limit the number of terms of office of members of the Congress, while José Serrano, a member of the House of Representatives (democracy, New York) wants to lift the two term limit for the President.
Congressman Jesse L. Jackson Jr. (democracy, Illinois) proposed many amendments to guarantee, among other things, the right to quality education and health care.
