The walls have eyes: How researchers study you on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Bering Bravik was just a regular guy who presented his anti-immigration views on the Internet.
On Monday, Bravik, who confessed to a massacre in Norway in July, which claimed 77 lives, appeared at his first public hearing.
Although Brayvik could act alone, he was far from alone on the net: he spent a lot of time preparing to attack his computer, communicating with millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the summer tragedy, researchers wanted to learn more about these people.
But how do we find them?
Easy, you just have to go to Facebook.
"We realized that it was not difficult to get close to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recently published report on European cyberpopulism at the British DEMOS Research Center.
The personal data on Facebook is so large, says Bartlett that researchers could easily use the website's promotional tool to identify the necessary demographic group with scientific accuracy -- that market scientists have been doing for several years.
Bartlett's team found half a million right-wing fans all over Europe and then posted ads to them, but instead of showing a new group or a diet product, the ads offered the user a survey that asked about their level of education, their attitude to violence, and their optimism about their own future.
With the help of Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 participants in 14 extreme right-wing parties in 11 European countries, not even leaving the office.
"It's a completely new way to do research," says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not as impressive: online right-wing groups are mostly male youths who are dissatisfied with immigration.
But suddenly, "those who combine their online activity with offline activity are more intelligent, more democratic and less aggressive than those who just hide behind the monitor."
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centres, medical researchers and polytologists use the site to study everything in the world, from health issues to social trends expressed in “Likes”, wall posts and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three entries per day, Facebook's “super-actual information” has caused a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the name of the site in the headline by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, Facebook’s beauty is that it provides an opportunity to study people who cannot be reached on the street with a notebook.
"In the past, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them."
"You would have had to join the party, and they would never have accepted you," Bartlett says.
"Facebook excludes all of this - you address them directly."
Others say that the site could identify and investigate social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues showed that students who discussed their drunken feats on Facebook were significantly more exposed to the risk of alcoholism than students who were silent about it.
Moreno suggests that student peers, such as their hostel mentors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who too often updates drinking status.
"You can't solve the problem without finding it," said Washington Post Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Centre for Child Health, Behaviour and Development at the Seattle Children's Research Institute.
"We found a way to identify children at risk who would not otherwise have been found."
Facebook also regularly extracts various kinds of data about its users.
The website's data processing team processed the status statistics for Valentine's Day, voter turnout in the middle of 2010, as well as the National happiness index (mainly using information that is only available to them - cyber free champions have long insisted that the site should make its extensive data collection publicly available for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not, in exchange for playing Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site can process your personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a study they don't even know about?
While researchers have strict standards for off-line research, online data is publicly available.
"I don't think many users have even thought that a researcher can watch their profiles," says Neil Selvin, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, "about a study he did in 2006 using publicly available Facebook pages.
"As far as they imagined, it was between them and their friends."
This raises the question of methodology.
Even offline, there's no guarantee that the subject of the study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is not possible to find out how much information on the profile and on the user's page is true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do outside Facebook are two completely different things," says Selvin.
That is why, despite years of work in the field of technology, Selwyn thinks that the notebook and pen are still the best research tools to be used.
"Nothing can replace a way into the real world and communicate with real people," he says.
"Social research is supposed to be about social research, and most social research is still offline."
