Seven lessons from Steve Jobs' lost interview, which is shown at the theater this week.
After Steve Jobs died on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, describing a technical genius as the Great Inventor of Modernity.
But what Apple fans can think of as the biggest discovery in the recently discovered interview, which was remembered in anticipation of the pre-shows in the main markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood in business processes and manufacturing technologies.
He was, of course, a designer, a dreamer and considered himself a hippie, but he was also a thorough organizer and modernizer of the production process, who believed that many business leaders suffered from "the disease of thinking that a really great idea is 90 per cent of the work... [but] a great idea separates a huge amount of skilled work from a great product."
Let's go back to 1995, Bob Kringley created a TV series called Triumph Nerds about the arrival of a personal computer, and he spent more than an hour with Jobs for a uniquely long conversation.
By that time, it had been about 10 years since Jobs was kicked out of Apple, and he was already working at his new computer company, NeXT, in anticipation of the massive development of the Internet.
While a small part of Kringley's interview was used in the Nerds, he says the original interviews were missing during transport.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full VHS copy was found in the director's garage.
This film, slightly edited, became the basis for the 68-minute film, Steve Jobs: Lost Interview, which is released on Landmark Theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For a man known for his hate for detailed interviews, Jobs seems unfamiliar here to express his technological philosophy and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
