The court will approve the “digital television” in Mexico in 2015.
Replacement of analogues with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme Court (JC) rejected the constitutional claims made by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the Presidential Decree, which moved the so-called “digital television” from 2021 to 2015, as eight votes were not obtained to cancel it.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Mesa, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his authority by issuing a decree detailing the steps taken to move to digital ground television.
As a result, the constitutional claims made by the Senate were rejected because of the absence of a qualified majority of eight votes required for the court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree and it remains in force.
The draft declaration, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed that the decree be declared unconstitutional because the regulation of the radio and television programme was a right established by law for the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and legislative reserve.
Only Salvidar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margaret Luna and Sanchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
On this point, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to disprove the decree and support the complaints, and Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions referred to in it regarding the transition to digital broadcasting.
It was also decided at the ministerial meeting to reject the request of the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the discussion of the draft, also under the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he disagreed with the arguments of the draft in the sense that the federal executive could not determine the general rules for the measures to be prepared by the public administration.
“I also do not believe that this would have affected the autonomy of the regulator” and recalled that planning public policy in strategic areas, such as the telecommunications sector, is relevant to the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate, State administration.
The replacement of analogue signals with digital signals, one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years, has led to better use of the radio-electric spectrum, better quality of the signal and more channels.
Postponing the transition, he said, would mean postponing the benefits of transforming into a digital form, which includes meeting public needs, which have not only a technical dimension “as it covers economic, social, political and national security issues”.
These questions, he said, “requests the work of the entire system of public economic governance, which includes a group of authorities, which the Constitution unites into the executive branch of the State”.
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed the transition to digital broadcasting and had done so with the help of the executive, despite the existence of highly specialized technical institutions.
It cannot be concluded from this that the Government, by adopting the decree under discussion, which in any event affects the competence of the Congress, ensures that the laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly are enforced in administrative matters.
In Michoacán, the possibility of counting "vote for vote" is being analysed.
According to the data transmitted to the EPRP, the difference between the first and second seats in the Governor ' s election is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes of 879 of the total of 6.074 protocols.
The possibility of counting a “vote vote” is real with regard to this year's electoral process in Michoacán, where, according to the Provisional Results Programme (PPP), the difference between the first and second seats in the Governor's elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting 879 of the total of 6.074 protocols.
In the light of this, the President of the General Council of the Michoacán Electoral Institute (IVM), Maria de Los Angeles Lianderal Saragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the Electoral Corps approved a set of principles to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
It should be recalled that Michoacán did not adopt the Constitution or the State Electoral Code or the Electoral Law, as the State Congress approved reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their entry into force in the electoral process and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel did not include its publication within the time frame specified in the State Official Gazette Act, stating that he had some objections.
On the same day, 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice (JJJJ) decided on a constitutional claim made by the local legislature and called the state representative's vote on constitutional reform “illegal and unlawful”, as it had no right to “authorize or support them”.
In an interview on the possibility of a “vote vote”, Maria de los Angeles Landeral argued that, with the adoption of suitable principles by the General Council of IWM, it would be possible to present a partial or complete count of votes by the local electoral authority.
For example, a partial recalculation of one or more ballot boxes may be made under the conditions that: the results of the records are not consistent; there is no record of voting and counting the documents in the urn or it is not in the hands of the chairman; or when there are obvious errors or corrections in the record.
In addition, the total recalculation of votes in all ballot boxes may occur when there is a sign that the difference between the alleged winner of the election in question and the second-rank candidate is less than or equal to one per cent, provided that at the beginning of the session there is a request from the representative of the party and/or coalition who has nominated the second of the candidates in question.
A total recalculation of votes will also be made if, at the end of the normal count, the difference between the winner and the second-place candidate is found to be less than or equal to 1 per cent, provided that there is a request from the political party whose candidate is the second-place candidate in the event that the ballot boxes, which have been included in the partial recalculation, are excluded.
It is worth noting that this is the case in Morelia, where according to PDRP, the difference between first place and second place is only 0.16 per cent, even if there are 129 votes out of a total of 923 protocols.
