A new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monty, will meet tomorrow with the Italian President to present a new government that will face the crisis that put this country on the verge of an economic catastrophe.
The appointed Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monty, will meet with the Italian President on Wednesday to present a new government that will face a crisis that put Italy on the verge of an economic catastrophe and damaged the entire eurozone.
A statement from the Presidential Palace stated that Monty, appointed on Sunday, would meet with the President, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he could form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed mainly of technocrats, although it is not clear when the new executive body will take its positions.
Monty said that he would present to the President the results of his negotiations with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to reaffirm my full confidence in our country's ability to get out of this difficult period," said the former European Commissioner to reporters.
Monty did not explicitly say that he was able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that the obstacles had been overcome.
"The paper is now well marked," he said.
Monty completed the government formation process in less than three days, much less than usual, as Italy was struggling with the political and financial crisis that brought their debt to a critical level.
The administration, under the leadership of former European Commissioner Monty, must approve the austerity package required by European leaders in order to restore confidence in Italy.
On the basis of pressure on Monty to rush it, unstable markets set the income from the BTP bonds of Italy by 10 years over 7 per cent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to be saved.
Emma Marchegalia, leader of the Italian Employers' Federation, told the reporters after meeting Monty, "We said we would actively support this government."
We believe that this government is Italy's last chance to get out of this critical situation.
Monty’s chances of success were largely based on the support of the LDP party, Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday because of the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monty's efforts should lead to a good outcome," said Angelino Alphano, secretary of the Centralist-Right Party.
The support of the LDP, the largest party in Italy, is important because so far many of its members have resisted the government majority of technocrats that form Monty.
Parliamentary support
The new Monty government must have strong parliamentary support for reforms that are likely to be unpopular in austerity reforms.
Any blocking or halting of these attempts could lead to a new and destructive attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks increased pressure, warning Monty that Monty’s failure could be a disaster.
Monty began his consultations on Monday with political parties, unions and business groups, as well as with youth and women's organizations.
He'll finish a series of his meetings on Tuesday night.
Monty was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who resolved an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a short break at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would retire, the value of Italy’s debt was now at a critical level, against the backdrop of uncertainty as to whether the new Prime Minister would succeed.
Salvaging Italy with a government debt of 1.8 billion euros would be too much for modern euro-zone financial defenders.
Monty said that his government would exist until the next elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians would only give him time to reform before he appointed a new election.
Monty said that he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that it should be composed only of technicians, evidence of their dissatisfaction with the financial situation affecting the process.
Political sources reported that the mutual distrust and dissent of the parties made it more difficult to attempt to include political figures.
