UNAM asphalt can avoid cracks
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Chemical Faculty, developed a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of best quality resistant to environmental and temperature effects.
If the signals sent by road cover were to be addressed, it would be necessary to repair about 200,000 pits for each rainy season in the Metropolitan Valley of Mexico City, says Rafael Herrera Naher, a researcher at the UNAM Chemical Faculty, and adds that if the construction and maintenance of asphalted road surfaces are correct, the number of pits can be reduced or reduced altogether.
In his lecture, the Technology View of the pits, read during the International Year of Chemistry, reports that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of characteristics close to bitumen but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nahera said that this type of modified bitumen could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and thus to resist the formation of pits.
He explained that bitumen, the hardest part of oil, was a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some were a high molecular mass called asphalts, and others were a low molecular mass called Maltens, which together gave road cover to its characteristic viscosity.
The viscous behavior of the bitumen is the fact that in high tempmeratures about 180 degrees it behaves like a liquid, at 120 its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it retains almost solid, while at very low temperatures the bitumen becomes fragile, he said.
This means that the resistance of the street asphalt is not permanent, but changes during the day, depending on the natural conditions and temperature, by a chemical engineer.
The chemist observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered with a flexible surface, composed of six layers of material, the last three of which include bitumen.
Among the top layers is a bitumen made of small stones, put into bitumen and then compressed.
Every stone that forms this coating, he said, is loaded in bitumen.
When vehicles are moving and effort is applied, this helps the forces to be very well distributed on the road surface.
If it were modified asphalt, they'd be even better distributed, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt cover, he added, there is the last layer, called the deterioration layer, which is made of small stones, actually sand also immersed in asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will be in contact with the wheels of the transport, it must have more resistance than asphalt coating and provide for road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and disseminate these forces, the wear layer also requires adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also very important factors for consideration, especially water, he said, because it has a significant impact on asphalt.
When the ground is raw, the water penetrates the surface and it's hard to get out of there, it makes all layers of the surface softened, and hence the formation of pits.
In the formation of the pits, he said, the first thing to wear is the wear layer and then it only affects the bitumen, but the damage doesn't happen instantly, which is a process that should be taken into account at the first signs of maintenance programmes.
A member of the National Research System also explained that transport is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each coating layer must always be linked to the transport load and must be guaranteed to meet this requirement in order to prevent the frequent occurrence of pits.
Rafael Herrera said that a lot of bitumen still needs to be studied and done, for example, with bitumen emulsions, which in other countries are already on the market and even help to repair pits lightly and without high temperatures.
