Difference in generosity only
In 2005, fear of entry into the country by a Polish plumber was felt by both the left and the right.
Both sides see immigration as a burden for the French economy and for French society.
The difference is only in the level of generosity they allow immigrants to show.
In his programme, François Hollande limited himself to banalism, saying that “joint work will solve our immigration problem”.
This notion of immigration as a burden and a problem may give an elective advantage, but it is economically expensive.
As the economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron remind us in a recent book summarizing recent immigration data (Special People: How Migration Made Our World and Determines Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Publication, 352 s.), there is a broad consensus among professionals on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries that accept immigrants.
Restriction of immigration reduces growth and reduces employment.
Fears of the influence of immigrants are based on the notion that they are able to replace local workers, especially low-skilled workers, by causing lower wages.
But experience has shown that, in reality, immigrants complement much more than replace local labour by performing jobs that lack local labour.
Unqualified immigrants work in sectors that do not attract local labour and the most skilled work in dynamic sectors where training is not about offering jobs.
Positive effects on wages
Just as it would be difficult for a surgeon to work in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, the complementarity between locals and immigrants has led to a positive effect on the wages of local workers.
Giovanni Peri estimated that a 1% increase in migration flows results in an 0.6-0.9% increase in real long-term wages.
