Moleskine Brand Notebook
Moleskine, created by an Italian company 15 years ago, will restore the taste of writing.
He has the aroma of adventures, hours spent after a letter in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easy to recognize by the rectangular black cover, by the rubber, by the yellow and white pages, as if yellowed over time.
However, the notebook Moleskine, as we know it today, was born in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided to launch design notebooks.
Maria Sebregondi, the company's then consultant, took responsibility for launching the new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old technique, the moleskin - laced cotton cloth used, for example, to cover the bench.
This type of notebook is said to be highly appreciated by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine aligned today's taste with the old and forgotten thing that was cultivating for the avant artists until the 20th century," said Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the control brand at Modo Modo.
Success has come.
From 2006 to 2010, sales increased by 25% to 12.7 million.
We were far from producing the first years when only 3,000 notebooks were produced.
Moleskine has crossed Italian borders and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to establish the profile of a typical buyer because the notebook attracts a businessman, a student, and a man of a free profession alike.
Moleskine buyers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and educated.
The small Italian company, which initially had only 12 employees, now has 100 and two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York.
It distributes its notebooks in Fnac bookshops, shops in small city centres, and has gained wide visibility.
"We followed the spirit of time and this new need for a letter despite the advent of e-mail," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This characteristic cultural feature accompanys the development of Moleskine; recently, the brand organized an exhibition entitled "The Great Way", where architects and artists exhibited their own notebooks.
In August, he also launched the cover of a leopard painting on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Using his success and cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified his products, which now include bags, pens, computer bags, and Brenda has all kinds of support.
The success of the envy: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, which added a new page to the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers so high?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for work.
The 15th week of employment for persons with disabilities begins today.
Despite the public charity policy launched in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average, 19 per cent against 9 per cent for the general population.
Dissatisfied?
"No," says Eric Blanche, Director General Adapt, an organization that organizes a week of employment for the disabled."
"Big progress has been made in 15 years."
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not two, but three times higher."
"But there's still a lot of work to do."
It must be said that there are still many barriers to employment for a disabled person.
Of these, 37 per cent are older than 50 years of age (17 per cent on average).
They are more likely to have low qualifications: 80 per cent do not have a bachelor ' s degree, while out of 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very common, which is 85 per cent for persons with disabilities, compared with an average of 38 per cent.
In short, these are all criteria that make it very difficult to get back to work and that are the core of the problem,” says Christian Grapin, Director General Trempling, an association established in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There's no need to talk about mentality that's changing, but it's too slow.
A study by IMS-Entreprendre, commissioned by Cité in April, revealed that the managers interviewed had a low level of knowledge of disability and “supposed to be full of people in wheelchairs or mentally or mentally disabled”.
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from having 6 per cent of disabled workers as set out in the Act of 1987.
The latest known figures for 2008 are 2.6 per cent.
"Today we're about 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, an organization responsible for collecting taxes from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: the number of “obligated” organizations, as well as the amounts paid, decreased from 59,000 to 46,000 in 2007-2011 (and from 606 million to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which raised the tax, created strong pressure on companies," Pierre Blanc explains.
“But this improvement also reflects a rise in awareness, particularly in large enterprises.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59 per cent of organizations with 20 to 49 employees have disabled workers, compared with 82 per cent of organizations with 100 to 199.
